    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im doing a lot of hiit lately and my legs feel like they are burning like crazy during the sprints. can u explain what is actually happening with the lactic acid in my muscles when that happens? and how does my body get rid of it after i stop?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, when you're doing high-intensity interval training (HIIT), your body shifts from using oxygen to produce energy to using a process called anaerobic respiration. This process generates lactic acid, which accumulates in your muscles, causing that burning sensation. \n\nTo get rid of it, your body eventually converts the lactic acid back into pyruvate, which can then be used in the mitochondria to produce energy again, or it can be converted into glucose in the liver. This process is called the Cori cycle. Once the lactic acid is cleared, your muscles should feel less sore, and you'll be ready to sprint again. Keep in mind that this process can take a bit of time, so don't be alarmed if you still feel some discomfort after your workout. Just remember, the burning feeling is a sign that your muscles are working hard, and it's part of the process of getting stronger and more efficient. Keep up the good work, and don't forget to rest and recover properly between workouts!",
      "source": "target",
